\f1\b\fs58 \cf2 \cb3 Key Concepts and Challenges in Pre-Market Trading\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa420\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs36 \cf2 \cb3 Pre-market trading usually has low volume and liquidity, leading to common large\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.investopedia.com/terms/b/bid-askspread.asp"}}{\fldrslt \cf8 \ul \ulc8 bid-ask spreads}}. Many retail brokers offer pre-market trading but may limit the types of orders that can be made during the pre-market period. Several\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.investopedia.com/terms/d/directaccessbroker.asp"}}{\fldrslt \cf8 \ul \ulc8 direct-access brokers}}\'a0allow pre-market trading to commence as early as 4 a.m. EST from Monday through Friday.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa420\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 Liquidity is very low, with most stocks displaying only\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.investopedia.com/terms/s/stub-quote.asp"}}{\fldrslt \cf8 \ul \ulc8 stub quotes}}. Index-based exchange-traded funds (ETFs), such as the SPDR S&P 500 ETF ({\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.investopedia.com/markets/quote?tvwidgetsymbol=SPY"}}{\fldrslt \cf8 \ul \ulc8 SPY}}), have moving quotes due to the trading in the S&P 500 futures contracts. Many of the most widely held\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.investopedia.com/terms/t/top-holdings.asp"}}{\fldrslt \cf8 \ul \ulc8 top holdings}}\'a0in benchmark indices may also get movement in the event of a significant gap up or down in the S&P 500 futures.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa120\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs58 \cf2 \cb3 An Overview of After-Hours Trading\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa420\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.investopedia.com/terms/a/afterhourstrading.asp"}}{\fldrslt 
\f0\b0\fs36 \cf8 \cb3 \ul \ulc8 After-hours trading}}
\f0\b0\fs36 \cb3 \'a0was introduced before pre-market trading. The New York Stock Exchange (NYSE) introduced after-hours trading in June 1991 by extending trading hours by an hour. The move was a response to increased competition from international exchanges in London and Tokyo and private exchanges, which offered more hours of trading, and 2.24 million shares changed hands in two sessions of trading.
\fs28 \cf8 \super 2
\fs36 \cf2 \cb1 \nosupersub \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa420\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 Over the years, as exchanges became increasingly computerized and the Internet's reach spread across borders, NYSE began extending the number of hours of trading available for trading, eventually allowing pre-market trading between the hours of 4 a.m. and 9:30 a.m.
\fs28 \cf8 \super 3
\fs36 \cf2 \cb1 \nosupersub \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa120\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs58 \cf2 \cb3 Advantages of Pre-Market Trading\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa420\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs36 \cf2 \cb3 Pre-market and after-hours trading, together called extended-hours trading, share similar benefits.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa120\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs46 \cf2 \cb3 Early Opportunities\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa420\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs36 \cf2 \cb3 Pre-market trading provides retail traders with an opportunity to react to overnight news before the regular trading session commences. Such news could be:\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls4\ilvl0\cf2 \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Corporate earnings\cb1 \
\ls4\ilvl0\cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
A major company announcement\cb1 \
\ls4\ilvl0\cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Overnight breaking news, such as geopolitical developments\cb1 \
\ls4\ilvl0\cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
News emanating from overseas markets.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa420\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 The caveat is that the pre-market reaction to such news may reverse in the regular trading session. The limited trading volume in the pre-market may provide a signal of weakness or strength that may not be borne out when the market opens and regular trading volumes are reached. For instance, a stock with an earnings miss may drop significantly in pre-market but could rise by the end of regular trading.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa120\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs46 \cf2 \cb3 Convenience\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa420\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs36 \cf2 \cb3 Pre-market hours benefit DIY traders who can't trade during regular market hours. The ability to start the day early and place trades in the pre-market is a big advantage for some due to the frenzied pace of everyday life.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa120\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs46 \cf2 \cb3 First Trades\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa420\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs36 \cf2 \cb3 Astute traders and investors familiar with trading patterns and experienced in extended-hours trading may use the pre-market to buy or sell stocks at more favorable prices compared to prices obtained by other traders in the regular session.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa420\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 This is only possible if the pre-market reaction to news about a stock is accurate and the stock does not fully discount the news in pre-market trading. In such instances, a stock that trades higher in the pre-market will continue to trend significantly higher in the regular trading session, while a stock that trades lower in the pre-market will trend lower during regular trading.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa120\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs58 \cf2 \cb3 Potential Risks in Pre-Market Trading\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa420\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs36 \cf2 \cb3 The extended trading hours also include several risks that can turn seemingly profitable opportunities into losses. Here are a few risks to be aware of.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa120\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs46 \cf2 \cb3 Limited Liquidity and Wide Bid-Ask Spreads\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa420\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs36 \cf2 \cb3 The number of buyers and sellers of stocks is far fewer in the pre-market compared with the multitudes of traders and investors during regular trading. As a result, pre-market trading volumes are generally a fraction of volumes in the regular session. Low trading volumes result in limited liquidity, greater volatility, and wide bid-ask spreads, which can trap a trader in a losing position.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa120\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs46 \cf2 \cb3 Price Uncertainty\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa420\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs36 \cf2 \cb3 Prices of stocks traded in the pre-market may diverge significantly from the prices of those same stocks during regular hours. Apart from the impact on stock prices from vastly differing trading volumes in pre-market and regular sessions, pre-market stock prices may only reflect prices from a single or handful of electronic communication networks (ECNs). During regular trading hours, multiple exchanges, ECNs, and market makers provide stock prices, leading to better\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.investopedia.com/terms/p/pricediscovery.asp"}}{\fldrslt \cf8 \ul \ulc8 price discovery}}. Additionally, the stock quotes shown are consolidated and represent the best bid and offer across all trading venues.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa120\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs46 \cf2 \cb3 Limit Orders May Result in Non-Execution\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa420\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs36 \cf2 \cb3 Many brokerages only accept limit orders in extended-hours trading to protect investors from unexpectedly adverse prices. Limit orders can only be executed at the limit price or better. The benefit of this feature of limit orders means that the trader knows the highest price at which a stock will be bought or the lowest price at which it will be sold. But this also means that if the market moves away from the limit price, the order will not be executed.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa120\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs46 \cf2 \cb3 Competition From Institutional Traders\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa420\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs36 \cf2 \cb3 Retail traders face an uneven playing field in pre-market trading because many of the participants are institutional and professional traders who have a trading edge on account of much deeper pockets and access to better, more timely information.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa420\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 Only experienced traders should consider pre-market trading, as the odds are against retail traders. Seasoned traders have the knowledge and experience to gauge the many nuances that make trading a challenge\'97such as assessing whether the pre-market reaction to the news is an under-reaction or over-reaction. They also know when to take decisive action on trading matters like opening a new stock position or closing an existing one, setting limit prices at certain levels for buys and sells, and so on.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa120\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs58 \cf2 \cb3 How to Engage in Pre-Market Trading Online\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa420\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs36 \cf2 \cb3 Most online brokers offer pre-market trading, but hours vary. Here's a sample of pre-market trading hours at select online brokers as of Dec. 21, 2021 (note that these hours may be subject to change):\cb1 \
