\fs52 \cf2 \cb3 What Time Is Pre-Market Trading?\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa420\partightenfactor0

\fs36 \cf2 \cb3 Pre-market trading can start as early as 4 a.m. EST, although most of it takes place from 8 a.m. EST and before regular trading commences at 9:30 a.m. EST.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa120\partightenfactor0

\fs52 \cf2 \cb3 Is Pre-Market Trading Worth It?\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa420\partightenfactor0

\fs36 \cf2 \cb3 While any trader can trade during pre-market hours, this period requires a high level of market awareness, strategy, and experience. For traders who can trade pre-market, it can be very profitable but can equally cause losses.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa120\partightenfactor0

\fs52 \cf2 \cb3 Does Pre-Market Affect Opening Prices?\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa420\partightenfactor0

\fs36 \cf2 \cb3 It can. Pre-market trades are the last prices before regular hours, so in reality, they can be opening prices. However, there is no guarantee that pre-market prices will stick.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa120\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs58 \cf2 \cb3 The Bottom Line\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa420\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs36 \cf2 \cb3 Pre-market trading allows investors to trade before the regular market session, offering early opportunities to react to news and events. Experienced traders can leverage these hours to capitalize on market movements, but the period is characterized by thin liquidity, wide bid-ask spreads, and potential price volatility. As a result, retail traders should approach pre-market sessions with caution, equipped with a solid strategy and a comprehensive understanding of the associated risks.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f3\b\fs56 \cf11 \cb12 Pre-market trading: What it is and how it works\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\qc\partightenfactor0

\f2\b0\fs28 \cf11 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs32 \cf11 \cb12 James Royal, Ph.D.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs28 \cf11 \cb12 February 9, 2024\'a05 min read\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\qc\partightenfactor0

\fs40 \cf11 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\qc\partightenfactor0

\fs28 \cf11 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa640\partightenfactor0

\fs40 \cf11 \cb12 Pre-market trading can be a good way to get into the market or out of it, particularly for widely followed stocks and funds. With pre-market trading, you can place trades before much of the market is ready to act. Despite this advantage, pre-market trading is not without some drawbacks.\cb1 \
\cb12 Here\'92s what pre-market trading is, how to do it and what to watch out for.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs28 \cf11 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f4\b\fs48 \cf11 \cb12 What is pre-market trading?\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa640\partightenfactor0

\f2\b0\fs40 \cf11 \cb12 Pre-market trading is\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.bankrate.com/investing/how-to-buy-stocks-online/?mf_ct_campaign=yahoo-synd-feed&utm_content=syndication"}}{\fldrslt \cf13 another way that you can trade stocks or ETFs}}, in addition to the regular daily hours and the after-hours sessions. Securities on the\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.bankrate.com/investing/new-york-stock-exchange/?mf_ct_campaign=yahoo-synd-feed&utm_content=syndication"}}{\fldrslt \cf13 New York Stock Exchange}}\'a0and Nasdaq are available to trade in the pre-market \'97 but only the largest, most liquid stocks and funds usually trade during this period.\cb1 \
\cb12 Trading in stocks and funds in the U.S. usually takes place during the hours of 9:30 a.m. to 4 p.m. Eastern time. Anything outside those times is considered extended hours, including pre-market trading, which runs from 4 a.m. to 9:30 a.m. Eastern time.\cb1 \
\cb12 The after-hours session runs from 4 p.m. to 8 p.m. Eastern time.\cb1 \
\cb12 Trading before the market opened used to be the province of wealthier clients, but now many online brokers, including\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.bankrate.com/investing/brokerage-reviews/charles-schwab/?mf_ct_campaign=yahoo-synd-feed&utm_content=syndication"}}{\fldrslt \cf13 Charles Schwab}}\'a0and\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.bankrate.com/investing/brokerage-reviews/fidelity/?mf_ct_campaign=yahoo-synd-feed&utm_content=syndication"}}{\fldrslt \cf13 Fidelity Investments}}, allow any client to trade during that window. However, many brokers do not allow customers to trade during the full pre-market trading period, often restricting them to the two and a half hours or so before the regular session.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs28 \cf11 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa640\partightenfactor0

\fs40 \cf11 \cb12 So, it\'92s not unusual for online brokers to allow pre-market trading to actually begin at 7 a.m.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f4\b\fs48 \cf11 \cb12 How to make trades during pre-market hours\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa640\partightenfactor0

\f2\b0\fs40 \cf11 \cb12 Making a pre-market trade is as easy as making a trade during regular hours, though it does present risks. Here\'92s how to set up your pre-market trade for buying and selling stocks and funds:\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f4\b \cf11 \cb12 1. Decide what you want to trade
\f5\b0 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa640\partightenfactor0

\f2 \cf11 \cb12 As you would for a trade during regular hours, you must input the stock or fund\'92s ticker symbol, the number of shares you want to trade, and the type of order you want to make \'97\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.bankrate.com/investing/limit-order-vs-market-order/?mf_ct_campaign=yahoo-synd-feed&utm_content=syndication"}}{\fldrslt \cf13 a limit order or market order}}, for example.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f4\b \cf11 \cb12 2. Set any trade conditions and time period
\f5\b0 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa640\partightenfactor0

\f2 \cf11 \cb12 If your broker allows you to set the time period, you can specify when you want the order to execute, with the following choices:\cb1 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls6\ilvl0
\f3\b \cf11 \cb12 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
In regular hours.
\f2\b0 \'a0This setting means the order will execute only during the regular session, when the market is generally most liquid.
\fs36 \cb1 \
\ls6\ilvl0
\f3\b\fs40 \cb12 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
In regular and extended hours.
\f2\b0 \'a0This setting will have your broker fill the order, if possible, during the regular session or the pre-market or after-hours sessions.
\fs36 \cb1 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa640\partightenfactor0
\ls6\ilvl0
\f3\b\fs40 \cf11 \cb12 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Only in extended hours.
\f2\b0 \'a0Your broker may allow you to set the trade to execute only during the pre-market or after-hours sessions, or only one of the sessions.
\fs36 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa640\partightenfactor0

\fs40 \cf11 \cb12 The market is much less liquid during the pre-market or after-hours trading sessions, so it makes a lot of sense to use limit orders. You\'92ll need to specify a price you\'92re willing to accept, but that helps you avoid the trade executing at a price that diverges wildly from the recent trading price of the security. Some brokers only allow for the use of limit orders in the extended sessions.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs28 \cf11 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f4\b\fs40 \cf11 \cb12 3. Place the trade
\f5\b0 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa640\partightenfactor0

\f2 \cf11 \cb12 After you set up the conditions for your trade, you\'92re ready to submit the trade to your broker.\cb1 \
\cb12 But don\'92t become alarmed if the trade doesn\'92t execute immediately, or even if it never does. Relatively few investors participate in pre-market or after-hours trading, and these periods don\'92t have market makers to ensure liquidity. For your order to execute, you\'92ll need to find someone who\'92s willing to do the trade at your price. The market may just not be available \'96 at any price.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f4\b\fs48 \cf11 \cb12 Risks of pre-market trading\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa640\partightenfactor0

\f2\b0\fs40 \cf11 \cb12 Pre-market trading presents some risks to investors who want to avail themselves of it:\cb1 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls7\ilvl0
\f3\b \cf11 \cb12 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Lack of liquidity.
\f2\b0 \'a0The pre-market session is much less liquid than the regular session, for most securities much of the time. You may not be able to trade at a price you\'92re willing to accept. And market makers and other liquidity providers won\'92t ensure an orderly market, as they would during normal trading. Only relatively few shares may trade, even for the large and typically liquid stocks.
\fs36 \cb1 \
\ls7\ilvl0
\f3\b\fs40 \cb12 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Inability to execute a trade.
\f2\b0 \'a0You can put an order in, but that doesn\'92t mean it will fill. And if no one wants to trade at your price, you\'92re out of luck. If you insist on trading at any price, you may end up with a much different execution price than you had otherwise intended.
\fs36 \cb1 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa640\partightenfactor0
\ls7\ilvl0
\f3\b\fs40 \cf11 \cb12 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Potential to misjudge sentiment.
\f2\b0 \'a0You might be looking to get out of or into a position after a big news event, such as a company\'92s earnings, before the rest of the market reacts. But the lack of liquidity in the pre-market may lead you to believe that a stock will sell off during the regular session, when it\'92s actually about to go up. Or vice versa. You can end up buying on what looks like a good earnings report, only for the market to plunge. Be careful.
\fs36 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs28 \cf11 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa640\partightenfactor0

\fs40 \cf11 \cb12 Those are the biggest concerns with trading the pre-market, and they all essentially concern the lack of liquidity that\'92s typical of most securities in the pre-market.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f4\b\fs48 \cf11 \cb12 Bottom line\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa640\partightenfactor0

\f2\b0\fs40 \cf11 \cb12 Pre-market trading lets you place trades outside the typical market hours, but that ability doesn\'92t mean you should do so. With a thin and illiquid market, it can be easy to make a trade at a bad price when you could wait a bit longer and get a better price in the more robust regular market.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
